[175.234912, "o", "\u001b[2m───\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[36m AI Analysis \u001b[0m\u001b[2m─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n# ReconKit Security Assessment Report\r\n\r\n## 1) Executive Summary\r\n\r\n- **Target**: scanme.nmap.org resolves to IPv4 address 45.33.32.156 and IPv6 address 2600:3c01::f03c:91ff:fe18:bb2f\r\n- **Open Services**: Two TCP ports exposed - SSH (22/tcp) and HTTP (80/tcp)\r\n- **SSH Service**: OpenSSH 6.6.1p1 Ubuntu 2ubuntu2.13 detected, which is an older version released in 2014\r\n- **Web Service**: Apache httpd 2.4.7 running on Ubuntu, serving a page titled \"Go ahead and ScanMe!\"\r\n- **Security Controls**: No Web Application Firewall (WAF) detected on the HTTP service\r\n- **DNS Configuration**: Only basic A/AAAA records present; no TXT, MX, CAA, NS, or SOA records found\r\n- **Scan Quality**: All tools executed successfully with no errors or timeouts\r\n\r\n## 2) Attack Surface Table\r\n\r\n| Port/Service | Evidence | Risk | Why It Matters | Validation Needed |\r\n|--------------|----------|------|----------------|-------------------|\r\n| 22/tcp - SSH | OpenSSH 6.6.1p1 Ubuntu 2ubuntu2.13 | Medium | Outdated SSH version may contain known vulnerabilities; provides remote access capability | Confirm exact OpenSSH version and check for authentication hardening |\r\n| 80/tcp - HTTP | Apache 2.4.7, Title: \"Go ahead and ScanMe!\" | Low-Medium | Web server exposure; no WAF protection; potential for web-based attacks | Verify web application content and check for common web vulnerabilities |\r\n\r\n## 3) Risk Assessment\r\n\r\n**Overall Risk: Medium**\r\n\r\nThe assessment reveals a relatively small attack surface with two exposed services. The primary concern is the outdated OpenSSH version (6.6.1p1 from 2014), which may contain unpatched vulnerabilities. The Apache web server (2.4.7) is also dated but serves only a simple informational page. The absence of a WAF and limited DNS records suggest minimal security infrastructure.\r\n\r\n**Confirmed Findings:**\r\n- SSH service running on port 22 with identifiable version string\r\n- HTTP service on port 80 with Apache 2.4.7\r\n- No WAF detected\r\n- Basic DNS resolution working\r\n\r\n**Assumptions:**\r\n- The SSH version may be vulnerable (requires CVE research)\r\n- The web page content is benign based on title alone\r\n\r\n## 4) How an Attacker Might Abuse This (Defensive View)\r\n\r\n- **SSH Brute Force/Credential Attacks**: The exposed SSH service could be targeted for brute-force login attempts or credential guessing against common accounts, especially given the older software version\r\n- **SSH Vulnerability Exploitation**: If the OpenSSH 6.6.1p1 version contains known vulnerabilities (such as CVE-2016-0777, CVE-2016-0778, or others from that era), attackers could attempt remote code execution or information disclosure\r\n- **Web Server Enumeration**: The Apache 2.4.7 server without WAF protection could be probed for directory traversal, default file exposure, or server misconfiguration vulnerabilities\r\n- **Protocol-Level Attacks**: Both services could be targeted for protocol-level exploitation attempts given their age and the lack of modern security controls\r\n\r\n## 5) Recommended Next Authorized Tests\r\n\r\n- `nmap -sV -p 22 --script ssh2-enum-algos,ssh-hostkey scanme.nmap.org` - Verify SSH algorithms and host key configuration\r\n- `nmap -sV -p 80 --script http-enum,http-headers scanme.nmap.org` - Check for hidden directories and HTTP security headers\r\n- `sslscan scanme.nmap.org:22` - If SSH supports TLS, check for weak cipher suites\r\n- `curl -I http://scanme.nmap.org` - Manually verify HTTP headers and server configuration\r\n- `nikto -h http://scanme.nmap.org` - Baseline web vulnerability scan (if authorized)\r\n- `ssh-audit scanme.nmap.org` - Detailed SSH security audit for configuration weaknesses\r\n\r\n## 6) Defensive Hardening Plan"]
[175.235065, "o", "\r\n\r\n1. **SSH Hardening**: \r\n   - Upgrade OpenSSH to current stable version\r\n   - Implement key-based authentication only\r\n   - Disable root login and password authentication\r\n   - Configure fail2ban or similar rate limiting\r\n   - Restrict SSH access via firewall to known IP ranges\r\n\r\n2. **Web Server Security**:\r\n   - Add security headers (X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.)\r\n   - Implement a WAF solution\r\n   - Keep Apache updated to latest stable version\r\n   - Configure proper access logging and monitoring\r\n\r\n3. **Network Controls**:\r\n   - Implement host-based firewall rules\r\n   - Consider port knocking or VPN-only access for SSH\r\n   - Monitor both services for suspicious activity\r\n\r\n4. **General Security**:\r\n   - Regular vulnerability scanning and patch management\r\n   - Enable comprehensive logging\r\n   - Establish incident response procedures\r\n\r\n## 7) Top 5 Priorities\r\n\r\n1. **Upgrade OpenSSH** - The SSH service is running a version from 2014 that likely contains unpatched security vulnerabilities\r\n2. **Implement SSH Access Controls** - Restrict SSH access via firewall rules or VPN to reduce attack surface\r\n3. **Deploy Web Application Firewall** - Add WAF protection to the HTTP service to defend against web-based attacks\r\n4. **Enable SSH Key Authentication** - Disable password authentication and enforce SSH key-based logins\r\n5. **Update Apache HTTP Server** - Upgrade to current Apache version to address potential vulnerabilities\r\n\r\n## 8) Data Quality Notes\r\n\r\nAll reconnaissance tools completed successfully with no errors, timeouts, or missing data. Service identification appears confident with clear version strings. The scan was performed in \"fast\" mode and completed in approximately 15 seconds, suggesting efficient but potentially limited scope. No WHOIS data was returned, which may indicate privacy protection or data source limitations.\r\n\u001b[32m\r\n[+] AI analysis saved: ai-report.md\u001b[0m\r\n"]
